  doi = {10.1175/JPO2813.1},
  abstract = {Repeated shipboard observation sections across the boundary flow off northeastern Brazil as well as acoustic Doppler current profiler (ADCP) and current-meter records from a moored boundary array deployed during 2000-04 near 11\textdegree S are analyzed here for both the northward warm water flow by the North Brazil Undercurrent (NBUC) above approximately 1100 m and the southward flow of North Atlantic Deep Water (NADW) underneath. At 5\textdegree S, the mean from nine sections yields an NBUC transport of 26.5 {$\pm$} 3.7 Sv (Sv {$\equiv$} 106 m3 s-1) along the boundary; at 11\textdegree S the mean NBUC transport from five sections is 25.4 {$\pm$} 7.4 Sv, confirming that the NBUC is already well developed at 11\textdegree S. At both latitudes a persistent offshore southward recirculation between 200- and 1100-m depth reduces the net northward warm water flow through the 5\textdegree S section (west of 31.5\textdegree W) to 22.1 {$\pm$} 5.3 Sv and through the 11\textdegree S section to 21.7 {$\pm$} 4.1 Sv (west of 32.0\textdegree W). The 4-yr-long NBUC transport time series from 11\textdegree S yields a seasonal cycle of 2.5 Sv amplitude with its northward maximum in July. Interannual NBUC transport variations are small, varying only by {$\pm$}1.2 Sv during the four years, with no detectable trend. The southward flow of NADW within the deep western boundary current at 5\textdegree S is 25.5 {$\pm$} 8.3 Sv with an offshore northward recirculation, yielding a nine-section mean of 20.3 {$\pm$} 10.1 Sv west of 31.5\textdegree W. For Antarctic Bottom Water, a net northward flow of 4.4 {$\pm$} 3.0 Sv is determined at 5\textdegree S. For the 11\textdegree S section, the moored array data show a pronounced energy maximum at 60-70-day period in the NADW depth range, which was identified in related work as deep eddies translating southward along the boundary. Based on a kinematic eddy model fit to the first half of the moored time series, the mean NADW transfer by the deep eddies at 11\textdegree S was estimated to be about 17 Sv. Given the large interannual variability of the deep near-boundary transport time series, which ranged from 14 to 24 Sv, the 11\textdegree S mean was considered to be not distinguishable from the mean at 5\textdegree S. \textcopyright{} 2005 American Meteorological Society.},
